    "divine_council_note": "1 Enoch 70 presents Enoch's entry into the divine council in its most exalted form. Enoch is brought before the 'Son of Man' (the Elect One), who in the Parables functions as the vice-regent of the Ancient of Days (God). This is the heavenly court in session — the same assembly glimpsed in Psalm 82:1, 1 Kings 22:19-22, Job 1:6-12, and Daniel 7:9-14. Enoch's 'name being raised aloft' suggests his formal installation into a position of authority within the council. In ANE royal courts, the king would 'raise the name' of a favored servant by publicly proclaiming their new status and authority. Here the metaphor is applied to the heavenly court: Enoch is given a permanent place among the divine beings who administer God's rule over creation. This is not deification (Enoch doesn't become God) but exaltation to a position of vice-regency under the Son of Man. The chapter thus presents a three-tiered hierarchy: (1) the Ancient of Days (God), (2) the Son of Man (Messiah/Elect One), (3) Enoch and the righteous, who share in the messianic administration.",
    
    "sections": [
        {
            "heading": "The Living Name Raised Aloft (70:1-2)",
            "body": "[C] The chapter opens with Enoch's 'living name' being raised up before the Son of Man and 'the Lord from among those who dwell upon the earth.' The phrase 'living name' (Hebrew: shem chai) is significant in Second Temple thought. In Hebrew anthropology, the 'name' represents the person's essence, reputation, and continuing presence. [B] To have one's name 'raised aloft' is to be publicly honored and given status. In royal contexts, this language describes promotion to high office (cf. Esther 3:1, where Haman's position is 'raised above' all other princes). <strong>Here the metaphor is applied to the heavenly court: Enoch is being formally installed into a position of authority in the divine council.</strong><br><br>[C] Verse 2 continues: 'And he was raised on the chariots of the spirit, and his name vanished among them.' The 'chariots of the spirit' (merkavot ha-ruach) is classic Merkavah mysticism language — the divine throne-chariot complex described in Ezekiel 1 and 10. Enoch is transported via the same means by which God moves through creation. His name 'vanishing among them' (the heavenly beings) suggests full integration into the angelic host — he becomes one of them, no longer merely a human visitor but a permanent resident of the heavenly realm.<br><br>[B] This transformation is theologically radical: it suggests that righteous humans can be elevated to share in the divine council's work. What was lost in Eden (access to the tree of life, walking with God in the garden-temple) can be restored — not through human effort but through divine initiative. Enoch becomes the prototype of eschatological humanity: what happened to him individually will happen corporately to the righteous at the resurrection (Daniel 12:3, 'those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above')."
        },
        {
            "heading": "From Earth to Heaven — The Geography of Translation (70:2-4)",
            "body": "[C] The text describes Enoch's ascent in spatial terms: he is taken from 'those who dwell upon the earth' to the realm where the Son of Man resides. In Second Temple cosmology, heaven was typically conceived as having multiple levels (Paul speaks of the 'third heaven' in 2 Corinthians 12:2; 2 Enoch describes seven heavens). <strong>The highest heaven is the throne room of God, where the divine council convenes and from which all authority flows.</strong><br><br>[C] 1 Enoch 70:3-4 states: 'And from that day I was not numbered among them, for he set me between two spirits, between the north and the west, where the angels took the cords to measure for me the place for the elect and righteous.' The 'two spirits' (likely winds or directional forces) and the 'cords to measure' evoke Ezekiel 40-48, where an angelic figure measures the eschatological temple. <strong>Enoch is being shown his assigned place in the heavenly temple — the permanent dwelling of the righteous.</strong><br><br>[B] The directional markers (north and west) may be significant. In Isaiah 14:13, the rebellious figure (often identified with Satan or a Babylonian king) boasts: 'I will sit on the mount of assembly in the far reaches of the north.' In Canaanite mythology, Mount Zaphon (north) was the dwelling place of the gods. Psalm 48:2 applies this imagery to Zion: 'Mount Zion, in the far north, the city of the great King.' [B] If Enoch is positioned between north and west, he may be stationed at a threshold position — between the earthly realm (west, where the sun sets) and the divine mountain (north, where God's throne is enthroned).<br><br>[C] The measuring of Enoch's place 'for the elect and righteous' indicates that his translation is not unique but representative. A place is being prepared for all who follow his path of righteousness. This theme reappears in John 14:2-3, where Jesus tells his disciples: 'In my Father's house are many rooms... I go to prepare a place for you.'"
        },
        {
            "heading": "Enoch and the Son of Man — The Encounter (70:1, cf. 71:14)",
            "body": "[C] Enoch is brought before the 'Son of Man' (bar enash in Aramaic, ben adam in Hebrew) — the central messianic figure of the Parables of Enoch. This figure is identified with the 'one like a son of man' in Daniel 7:13-14, who receives everlasting dominion from the Ancient of Days. In the Parables, the Son of Man is also called the Elect One, the Righteous One, and the Anointed One (Messiah). <strong>He functions as God's vice-regent, the chief executor of divine judgment and salvation.</strong><br><br>[B] The relationship between Enoch and the Son of Man is complex and debated. In 1 Enoch 71:14, Enoch is told: 'You are the Son of Man who was born to righteousness.' Some scholars argue this identifies Enoch with the Son of Man (making Enoch himself the Messiah-figure). Others contend the text means Enoch is <em>like</em> the Son of Man or is being conformed to his image. The latter reading is more coherent with the overall narrative: Enoch remains a distinct figure who serves the Son of Man, but through his translation and transformation, he comes to share in the Son of Man's glory and authority.<br><br>[A] This pattern of righteous humans being conformed to a heavenly archetype appears throughout Scripture. Romans 8:29 states that believers are 'predestined to be conformed to the image of his Son.' Philippians 3:21 promises that Christ 'will transform our lowly body to be like his glorious body.' 1 John 3:2 declares: 'When he appears we shall be like him, because we shall see him as he is.' [B] Enoch's transformation before the Son of Man is the prototype of this eschatological conformity.<br><br>[C] The throne room setting is crucial. In ANE royal ideology, to stand before the king is to have access to his presence and authority. Joseph stands before Pharaoh (Genesis 41:46), Daniel before Nebuchadnezzar (Daniel 2:46-49), Nehemiah before Artaxerxes (Nehemiah 2:1-8). In each case, proximity to the throne grants delegated authority. <strong>Enoch's position before the Son of Man indicates he has been granted a role in the messianic administration of the cosmos.</strong>"
        },
        {
            "heading": "The Theology of Translation — Bypassing Death",
            "body": "[A] Genesis 5:24 is the foundational text: 'Enoch walked with God, and he was not, for God took him.' The verb 'took' (laqach) is the same used in 2 Kings 2:3 for Elijah's translation. The Septuagint translates it with metatithēmi (to transfer, translate), which becomes the technical term for assumption into heaven. Hebrews 11:5 uses this verb: 'By faith Enoch was translated (metatithēmi) so that he should not see death.'<br><br>[B] Translation theology addresses a fundamental human anxiety: the inevitability of death. From the moment Adam and Eve are expelled from Eden and barred from the tree of life (Genesis 3:22-24), death becomes the universal human fate (Genesis 3:19, 'dust you are, and to dust you shall return'). <strong>But if Enoch can bypass death through righteousness and divine favor, then death is not absolute — it can be overcome.</strong><br><br>[C] This hope becomes central to Second Temple Judaism. Daniel 12:2-3 promises: 'Many of those who sleep in the dust of the earth shall awake, some to everlasting life... And those who are wise shall shine like the brightness of the sky above.' The Wisdom of Solomon 3:1-9 declares that 'the souls of the righteous are in the hand of God, and no torment will ever touch them.' 2 Maccabees 7 presents the martyrdom of seven brothers who die confident in the resurrection: 'The King of the universe will raise us up to an everlasting renewal of life' (7:9).<br><br>[A] In the New Testament, Jesus' resurrection becomes the ultimate vindication of translation theology. 1 Corinthians 15:20-23 declares Christ 'the firstfruits of those who have fallen asleep,' guaranteeing that 'in Christ shall all be made alive.' Enoch and Elijah are the preview; Christ is the guarantee; the resurrection of the dead is the full harvest.<br><br>[C] Rabbinic tradition struggled with Enoch. Some rabbis (e.g., Rabbi Aibu in Genesis Rabbah 25:1) argued that Enoch was actually taken in judgment, not honor, because he was unstable in righteousness. This reflects rabbinic discomfort with the exaltation of Enoch in works like 1 Enoch and 3 Enoch (where Enoch becomes Metatron). But the earlier Second Temple consensus was clear: Enoch's translation was the reward of righteousness and a sign of hope for all who walk with God."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Enoch as Intercessor and Witness — The Ongoing Role",
            "body": "[C] Enoch's translation is not retirement from earthly concerns but a repositioning for ongoing ministry. Throughout 1 Enoch, he functions as intercessor (chapters 13-16, where he pleads for the Watchers), scribe (recording the deeds of humanity for judgment), and prophet (announcing coming judgment). His translation intensifies these roles rather than ending them.<br><br>[C] Jubilees 4:23 states that Enoch 'was taken from among the children of men, and we conducted him into the Garden of Eden for greatness and honor, and behold he writes down the judgment and condemnation of the world, and all the wickedness of the children of men.' Enoch is positioned in Eden — the earthly temple-garden where heaven and earth meet — to serve as witness against human sin and angelic rebellion. <strong>His role parallels that of the two witnesses in Revelation 11:3-12, who prophesy, are killed, and then ascend to heaven in a cloud (echoing Enoch and Elijah's translation pattern).</strong><br><br>[B] This intercessory role is grounded in Enoch's unique position: he is human (understanding human frailty) but has been translated to heaven (having access to God's presence). He is the bridge figure par excellence. Hebrews 7:25 says of Jesus: 'He is able to save to the uttermost those who draw near to God through him, since he always lives to make intercession for them.' [B] Enoch's intercessory role prefigures Christ's high priestly ministry.<br><br>[C] In Merkavah mysticism (3 Enoch), Enoch-Metatron sits at the entrance to the seventh heaven, recording the merits and demerits of Israel. He is called 'the Youth' (na'ar) and 'the lesser YHWH,' given authority to sit on a throne (a privilege otherwise forbidden to angels). This represents the ultimate development of Enochic exaltation theology: the translated human becomes the chief administrative officer of the divine council, second only to God himself.<br><br>[B] While 3 Enoch's claims exceed what canonical Scripture affirms, the core principle is biblical: righteous humans can be elevated to share in God's administrative rule over creation. Daniel 7:18, 22, 27 promises that 'the saints of the Most High shall receive the kingdom and possess the kingdom forever.' Revelation 3:21 promises: 'The one who conquers, I will grant him to sit with me on my throne.' [B] Enoch's translation is the prototype of this eschatological enthronement of the righteous."
        },
        {
            "heading": "Translation and Transformation — Ontological Change",
            "body": "[C] 2 Enoch 22:8-10 provides the most vivid description of Enoch's transformation: 'The Lord said to Michael, "Go, and extract Enoch from his earthly clothing. And anoint him with my delightful oil, and put him into the clothes of my glory." And so Michael did, just as the Lord had said to him. He anointed me and he clothed me. And the appearance of that oil is greater than the greatest light... and its ointment is like sweet dew, and its fragrance myrrh; and it is like the rays of the glittering sun. And I looked at myself, and I had become like one of his glorious ones, and there was no observable difference.'<br><br>[B] This passage reveals that translation involves not just spatial relocation (earth to heaven) but <strong>ontological transformation</strong> — a change in the very nature of one's being. Enoch's earthly body is exchanged for a glorified body. He is anointed (like a priest or king) and clothed in 'garments of glory' (a phrase used in Qumran texts for the eschatological state of the righteous). The result: Enoch becomes 'like one of his glorious ones' — indistinguishable from the angels.<br><br>[A] This transformation theology is deeply biblical. Philippians 3:21 promises that Christ 'will transform our lowly body to be like his glorious body, by the power that enables him even to subject all things to himself.' 1 Corinthians 15:51-53 declares: 'We shall not all sleep, but we shall all be changed... For this perishable body must put on the imperishable, and this mortal body must put on immortality.' [B] What happened to Enoch individually will happen to all believers corporately at the resurrection/rapture.<br><br>[C] The 'garments of glory' motif connects to Adam and Eve in Eden. Jubilees 3:26 states that Adam and Eve were 'clothed with glory' before the fall, which they lost when they sinned. Genesis Rabbah 20:12 interprets Genesis 3:21 ('the LORD God made for Adam and for his wife garments of skins') as a diminishment: they had worn 'garments of light' (Hebrew: or) but received 'garments of skin' (Hebrew: or with different vowels). [B] Enoch's translation reverses the fall: he is re-clothed in the glory Adam lost, restored to the Edenic state of walking with God in the garden-temple.<br><br>[C] The transformation is not just physical but epistemological. 2 Enoch 23:1-6 describes Enoch being shown 'the books of the storehouses' and learning 'all the things in heaven and on earth and in the sea.' He gains comprehensive knowledge of creation, past, present, and future. This echoes the promise of the tree of knowledge in Eden — but here the knowledge is granted by God as a gift, not seized in rebellion. <strong>The translated Enoch becomes the archetypal sage, the model of wisdom attained through righteousness rather than presumption.</strong>"
